# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quaternions-octonions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] In mathematics, the **Cayley–Dickson construction**, sometimes also known as the **Cayley–Dickson process** or the **Cayley–Dickson procedure** produces a sequence of algebras over the field of real numbers, each with twice the dimension of the previous one.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] It is named after Arthur Cayley and Leonard Eugene Dickson.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The algebras produced by this process are known as **Cayley–Dickson algebras**, for example complex numbers, quaternions, and octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] These examples are useful composition algebras frequently applied in mathematical physics.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The Cayley–Dickson construction defines a new algebra as a Cartesian product of an algebra with itself, with multiplication defined in a specific way (different from the componentwise multiplication) and an involution known as *conjugation*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The product of an element and its conjugate (or sometimes the square root of this product) is called the norm.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The symmetries of the real field disappear as the Cayley–Dickson construction is repeatedly applied: first losing order, then commutativity of multiplication, associativity of multiplication, and finally alternativity.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] More generally, the Cayley–Dickson construction takes any algebra with involution to another algebra with involution of twice the dimension.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The **Cayley–Dickson construction** is due to Leonard Dickson in 1919 showing how the octonions can be constructed as a two-dimensional algebra over quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] In fact, starting with a field *F*, the construction yields a sequence of *F*-algebras of dimension 2*n*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] For *n* = 2 it is an associative algebra called a quaternion algebra, and for *n* = 3 it is an alternative algebra called an octonion algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] These instances *n* = 1, 2 and 3 produce composition algebras as shown below.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The case *n* = 1 starts with elements (*a*, *b*) in *F* × *F* and defines the conjugate (*a*, *b*)* to be (*a**, –*b*) where *a** = *a* in case *n* = 1, and subsequently determined by the formula.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] + terms that cancel by the associative property.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] A complex number whose second component is zero is associated with a real number: the complex number (*a*, 0) is associated with the real number a.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] since a is a real number and is its own conjugate.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] As a complex number consists of two independent real numbers, they form a two-dimensional vector space over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] Besides being of higher dimension, the complex numbers can be said to lack one algebraic property of the real numbers: a real number is its own conjugate.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The next step in the construction is to generalize the multiplication and conjugation operations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] Slight variations on this formula are possible; the resulting constructions will yield structures identical up to the signs of bases.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The order of the factors seems odd now, but will be important in the next step.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] These operators are direct extensions of their complex analogs: if a and b are taken from the real subset of complex numbers, the appearance of the conjugate in the formulas has no effect, so the operators are the same as those for the complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] As before, the conjugate thus yields a norm and an inverse for any such ordered pair.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] So in the sense we explained above, these pairs constitute an algebra something like the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] They are the quaternions, named by Hamilton in 1843.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] As a quaternion consists of two independent complex numbers, they form a four-dimensional vector space over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The multiplication of quaternions is not quite like the multiplication of real numbers, though; it is not commutative – that is, if p and q are quaternions, it is not always true that *pq* = *qp*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] All the steps to create further algebras are the same from octonions onwards.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] For exactly the same reasons as before, the conjugation operator yields a norm and a multiplicative inverse of any nonzero element.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] Graves in 1843, and is called the octonions or the "Cayley numbers".
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] As an octonion consists of two independent quaternions, they form an eight-dimensional vector space over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The multiplication of octonions is even stranger than that of quaternions; besides being non-commutative, it is not associative – that is, if p, q, and r are octonions, it is not always true that (*pq*)*r* = *p*(*qr*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] For the reason of this non-associativity, octonions have no matrix representation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The algebra immediately following the octonions is called the sedenions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] It retains the algebraic property of power associativity, meaning that if s is a sedenion, *snsm* = *s**n* + *m*, but loses the property of being an alternative algebra and hence cannot be a composition algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The algebra immediately following the sedenions is the trigintaduonions, which form a 32-dimensional algebra over the real numbers and can be represented by blackboard bold $\mathbb {T}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The Cayley–Dickson construction can be carried on *ad infinitum*, at each step producing a power-associative algebra whose dimension is double that of the algebra of the preceding step.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] These include the 64-dimensional sexagintaquatronions (or 64-nions), the 128-dimensional centumduodetrigintanions (or 128-nions), the 256-dimensional ducentiquinquagintasexions (or 256-nions), and *ad infinitum*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] All the algebras generated in this way over a field are *quadratic*: that is, each element satisfies a quadratic equation with coefficients from the field.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] Schafer proved that the algebras generated by the Cayley–Dickson process over a field F satisfy the flexible identity.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] He also proved that any derivation algebra of a Cayley–Dickson algebra is isomorphic to the derivation algebra of Cayley numbers, a 14-dimensional Lie algebra over F.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The Cayley–Dickson construction, starting from the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ , generates the composition algebras $\mathbb {C}$ (the complex numbers), $\mathbb {H}$ (the quaternions), and $\mathbb {O}$ (the octonions).
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] Applying the original Cayley–Dickson construction to the split-complexes also results in the split-quaternions and then the split-octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] for γ an additive map that commutes with * and left and right multiplication by any element.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] The algebra *B* = *A* ⊕ *A* produced by the Cayley–Dickson construction is also an algebra with involution.
[src:quaternions-octonions/cayley-dickson-construction] B inherits properties from A unchanged as follows.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] In mathematics, the **octonions** are a normed division algebra over the real numbers, a kind of hypercomplex number system.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The octonions are usually represented by the capital letter O, using boldface **O** or blackboard bold $\mathbb {O}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Octonions have eight dimensions; twice the number of dimensions of the quaternions, of which they are an extension.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] They are noncommutative and nonassociative, but satisfy weaker forms of associativity; they are alternative and power associative.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Octonions are much less widely studied or used than the quaternions and complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Octonions are related to exceptional structures in mathematics, among them the exceptional Lie groups.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Octonions have applications in fields such as string theory, special relativity and quantum logic.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The Cayley–Dickson construction builds the octonions from the quaternions and in turn builds the sedenions from the octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The octonions were discovered in December 1843 by John T.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Graves, inspired by his friend William Rowan Hamilton's discovery of quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Graves called his discovery "octaves", and mentioned them in a letter to Hamilton dated 26 December 1843.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] He first published his result slightly later than Arthur Cayley's article.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The octonions were discovered independently by Cayley and are sometimes referred to as **Cayley numbers** or the **Cayley algebra**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Hamilton described the early history of Graves's discovery.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The octonions can be thought of as octets (or 8-tuples) of real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] where *e*0 is the scalar or real element; it may be identified with the real number 1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] A more systematic way of defining the octonions is via the Cayley–Dickson construction.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Applying the Cayley–Dickson construction to the quaternions produces the octonions, which can be expressed as $\mathbb {O} ={\mathcal {CD}}(\mathbb {H} ,1)$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Much as quaternions can be defined as pairs of complex numbers, the octonions can be defined as pairs of quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] where *z** denotes the conjugate of the quaternion z.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Addition and subtraction of octonions is done by adding and subtracting corresponding terms and hence their coefficients, like quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Multiplication of octonions is more complex.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Multiplication is distributive over addition, so the product of two octonions can be calculated by summing the products of all the terms, again like quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The product of each pair of terms can be given by multiplication of the coefficients and a multiplication table of the unit octonions, like this one (given both by Arthur Cayley in 1845 and John T.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Most off-diagonal elements of the table are antisymmetric, making it almost a skew-symmetric matrix except for the elements on the main diagonal, as well as the row and column for which *e*0 is an operand.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Whenever any two of the three indices are the same, *ε**ℓmn* = 0.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The above definition is not unique: it is one of 480 possible definitions for octonion multiplication with *e*0 = 1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The others can be obtained by permuting and changing the signs of the non-scalar basis elements {*e*1, *e*2, *e*3, *e*4, *e*5, *e*6, *e*7}.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The 480 different algebras are isomorphic, and there is rarely a need to consider which particular multiplication rule is used.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Each of these 480 definitions is invariant up to signs under some 7 cycle of the points (1 2 3 4 5 6 7), and for each 7 cycle there are four definitions, differing by signs and reversal of order.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] A variant of this sometimes used is to label the elements of the basis by the elements ∞, 0, 1, 2, ..., 6, of the projective line over the finite field of order 7.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The multiplication is then given by *e*∞ = 1 and *e*1*e*2 = *e*4, and all equations obtained from this one by adding a constant (modulo 7) to all subscripts: In other words using the seven triples (1 2 4), (2 3 5), (3 4 6), (4 5 0), (5 6 1), (6 0 2), (0 1 3).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] These are the nonzero codewords of the quadratic residue code of length 7 over the Galois field of two elements, *GF*(2).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] There is a symmetry of order 7 given by adding a constant mod 7 to all subscripts, and also a symmetry of order 3 given by multiplying, modulo 7, all subscripts by one of the quadratic residues 1, 2, and 4.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] These seven triples can also be considered as the seven translates of the set {1,2,4} of non-zero squares forming a cyclic (7,3,1)-difference set in the finite field GF(7) of seven elements.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] If the ★ is forced to be equal to the identity, then the multiplication ceases to be associative, but the ★ may be removed from the multiplication table resulting in an octonion multiplication table.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] In keeping ★ = *i* *j* *k* *l* associative and thus not reducing the 4-dimensional geometric algebra to an octonion one, the whole multiplication table can be derived from the equation for ★.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Consider the gamma matrices in the examples given above.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The formula defining the fifth gamma matrix ( $\gamma _{5}$ ) shows that it is the ★ of a four-dimensional geometric algebra of the gamma matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] A convenient mnemonic for remembering the products of unit octonions is given by the diagram, which represents the multiplication table of Cayley and Graves.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] This diagram with seven points and seven lines (the circle through 1, 2, and 3 is considered a line) is called the Fano plane.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The seven points correspond to the seven standard basis elements of $\operatorname {\mathcal {I_{m}}} {\bigl [}\mathbb {O} {\bigr ]}$ (see definition under *§ Conjugate, norm, and inverse* below).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Each pair of distinct points lies on a unique line and each line runs through exactly three points.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Let (*a*, *b*, *c*) be an ordered triple of points lying on a given line with the order specified by the direction of the arrow.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Then multiplication is given by *ab* = *c* and *ba* = −*c* together with cyclic permutations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] completely defines the multiplicative structure of the octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Each of the seven lines generates a subalgebra of $\mathbb {O}$ isomorphic to the quaternions ℍ.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Conjugation is an involution of $\ \mathbb {O} \$ and satisfies (*xy*)* = *y***x** (note the change in order).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The set of all purely imaginary octonions spans a 7-dimensional subspace of $\mathbb {O} ,$ denoted $\operatorname {\mathcal {I_{m}}} {\bigl [}\mathbb {O} {\bigr ]}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] This norm agrees with the standard 8-dimensional Euclidean norm on ℝ8.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] also sometimes called scalar and vector parts.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The octonions do satisfy a weaker form of associativity: they are alternative.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] This means that the subalgebra generated by any two elements is associative.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Actually, one can show that the subalgebra generated by any two elements of $\ \mathbb {O} \$ is isomorphic to ℝ, ℂ, or ℍ, all of which are associative.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Because of their non-associativity, octonions cannot be represented by a subalgebra of a matrix ring over ℝ, unlike the real numbers, complex numbers, and quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] This equation means that the octonions form a composition algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The higher-dimensional algebras defined by the Cayley–Dickson construction (starting with the sedenions) all fail to satisfy this property.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Wider number systems exist which have a multiplicative modulus (for example, 16-dimensional conic sedenions).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Their modulus is defined differently from their norm, and they also contain zero divisors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] As shown by Hurwitz, ℝ, ℂ, or ℍ, and $\mathbb {O}$ are the only normed division algebras over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] These four algebras also form the only alternative, finite-dimensional division algebras over the real numbers (up to an isomorphism).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Not being associative, the nonzero elements of $\mathbb {O}$ do not form a group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] They do, however, form a loop, specifically a Moufang loop.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] But like the octonion product it is not uniquely defined.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Instead there are many different cross products, each one dependent on the choice of octonion product.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The set of all automorphisms of $\mathbb {O}$ forms a group called *G*2.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The group *G*2 is a simply connected, compact, real Lie group of dimension 14.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] This group is the smallest of the exceptional Lie groups and is isomorphic to the subgroup of Spin(7) that preserves any chosen particular vector in its 8-dimensional real spinor representation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The group Spin(7) is in turn a subgroup of the group of isotopies described below.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] An isotopy of an algebra is a triple of bijective linear maps a, b, c such that if *xy* = *z* then *a*(*x*)*b*(*y*) = *c*(*z*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] For *a* = *b* = *c* this is the same as an automorphism.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The isotopy group of an algebra is the group of all isotopies, which contains the group of automorphisms as a subgroup.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The isotopy group of the octonions is the group Spin8(ℝ), with a, b, c acting as the three 8-dimensional representations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The subgroup of elements where c fixes the identity is the subgroup Spin7(ℝ), and the subgroup where a, b, c all fix the identity is the automorphism group *G*2 .
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Just as quaternions can be represented as matrices, octonions can be represented as tables of quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The octonions play a significant role in the classification and construction of other mathematical entities.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] For example, the exceptional Lie group G2 is the automorphism group of the octonions, and the other exceptional Lie groups F4, E6, E7 and E8 can be understood as the isometries of certain projective planes defined using the octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The set of self-adjoint 3 × 3 octonionic matrices, equipped with a symmetrized matrix product, defines the Albert algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] In discrete mathematics, the octonions provide an elementary derivation of the Leech lattice, and thus they are closely related to the sporadic simple groups.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Applications of the octonions to physics have largely been conjectural.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] For example, in the 1970s, attempts were made to understand quarks by way of an octonionic Hilbert space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] It is known that the octonions, and the fact that only four normed division algebras can exist, relates to the spacetime dimensions in which supersymmetric quantum field theories can be constructed.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Also, attempts have been made to obtain the Standard Model of elementary particle physics from octonionic constructions, for example using the "Dixon algebra" $\mathbb {C} \otimes \mathbb {H} \otimes \mathbb {O}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Octonions have also arisen in the study of black hole entropy, quantum information science, string theory, and image processing.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Octonions have been used in solutions to the hand eye calibration problem in robotics.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Deep octonion networks provide a means of efficient and compact expression in machine learning applications.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] There are several natural ways to choose an integral form of the octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The simplest is just to take the octonions whose coordinates are integers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] This gives a nonassociative algebra over the integers called the Gravesian octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] However it is not a maximal order (in the sense of ring theory); there are exactly seven maximal orders containing it.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] These seven maximal orders are all equivalent under automorphisms.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The phrase "integral octonions" usually refers to a fixed choice of one of these seven orders.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] These maximal orders were constructed by Kirmse (1924), Dickson and Bruck as follows.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Label the eight basis vectors by the points of the projective line over the field with seven elements.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] of the extended quadratic residue code of length 8 over the field of two elements, given by ∅, (∞124) and its images under adding a constant modulo 7, and the complements of these eight sets.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] Then switch infinity and any one other coordinate; this operation creates a bijection of the Kirmse integers onto a different set, which is a maximal order.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] There are seven ways to do this, giving seven maximal orders, which are all equivalent under cyclic permutations of the seven coordinates 0123456.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The Kirmse integers and the seven maximal orders are all isometric to the E8 lattice rescaled by a factor of 1/√2.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] In particular there are 240 elements of minimum nonzero norm 1 in each of these orders, forming a Moufang loop of order 240.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The integral octonions have a "division with remainder" property: given integral octonions a and *b* ≠ 0, we can find q and r with *a* = *qb* + *r*, where the remainder r has norm less than that of b.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] In the integral octonions, all left ideals and right ideals are 2-sided ideals, and the only 2-sided ideals are the principal ideals nO where n is a non-negative integer.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The integral octonions have a version of factorization into primes, though it is not straightforward to state because the octonions are not associative so the product of octonions depends on the order in which one does the products.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The irreducible integral octonions are exactly those of prime norm, and every integral octonion can be written as a product of irreducible octonions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] More precisely an integral octonion of norm mn can be written as a product of integral octonions of norms m and n.
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The automorphism group of the integral octonions is the group G2(**F**2) of order 12,096, which has a simple subgroup of index 2 isomorphic to the unitary group 2*A*2(32).
[src:quaternions-octonions/octonion] The isotopy group of the integral octonions is the perfect double cover of the group of rotations of the E8 lattice.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In mathematics, the **quaternions** form a number system similar to the complex numbers, with the usual arithmetical operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division, but with four real-number components instead of two.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Unlike with the complex numbers, quaternion multiplication is not commutative, meaning that the result of multiplying two quaternions depends on their order.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Quaternions can be used to represent vectors in three-dimensional space, which provides a definition of the quotient of two vectors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Quaternions were first described by the Irish mathematician and physicist William Rowan Hamilton in 1843, and in his honor the set of all quaternions is conventionally denoted by $\mathbb {H}$ or **H**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A generic quaternion is usually represented in the form $a+b\,\mathbf {i} +c\,\mathbf {j} +d\,\mathbf {k} ,$ where the coefficients a, b, c, d are real numbers, and 1, **i**, **j**, **k** are the *basis vectors* or *basis elements*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] They can be used alongside other methods of rotation, such as Euler angles and rotation matrices, or as an alternative to them, depending on the application.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] As an abstract mathematical structure, quaternions form a four-dimensional associative normed division algebra over the real numbers, and therefore a ring, also a division ring and a domain.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Because of their non-commutative multiplication, they do not form a field.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] According to the Frobenius theorem, the algebra $\mathbb {H}$ is one of only two finite-dimensional division rings containing a proper subring isomorphic to the real numbers; the other being the complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] These rings are also Euclidean Hurwitz algebras, of which the quaternions are the largest associative algebra (and hence the largest ring).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Further extending the quaternions yields the non-associative octonions, which is the last normed division algebra over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The next extension gives the sedenions, which have zero divisors and so cannot be a normed division algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The unit quaternions give a group structure on the 3-sphere S3 isomorphic to the groups Spin(3) and SU(2), i.e. the universal cover group of SO(3).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The positive and negative basis vectors form the eight-element quaternion group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Quaternions were introduced by Hamilton in 1843.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Important precursors to this work included Euler's four-square identity (1748) and Olinde Rodrigues' parameterization of general rotations by four parameters (1840), but neither of these writers treated the four-parameter rotations as an algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Gauss had discovered quaternions in 1819, but this work was not published until 1900.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Hamilton knew that the complex numbers could be interpreted as points in a plane, and he was looking for a way to do the same for points in three-dimensional space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Points in space can be represented by their coordinates, which are triples of numbers, and for many years he had known how to add and subtract triples of numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] However, for a long time, he had been stuck on the problem of multiplication and division.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] He could not figure out how to calculate the quotient of the coordinates of two points in space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The great breakthrough in quaternions finally came on Monday 16 October 1843 in Dublin, when Hamilton was on his way to the Royal Irish Academy to preside at a council meeting.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] As he walked along the towpath of the Royal Canal with his wife, the concepts behind quaternions were taking shape in his mind.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Although the carving has since faded away, there has been an annual pilgrimage since 1989, called the *Hamilton Walk*, for scientists and mathematicians who process from the Dunsink Observatory to the Royal Canal bridge in remembrance of Hamilton's discovery.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] On the following day, Hamilton wrote a letter to his friend and fellow mathematician, J.T.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Graves, describing the train of thought that led to his discovery.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Hamilton called a quadruple with these rules of multiplication a *quaternion*, and he devoted most of the remainder of his life to studying and teaching them.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Hamilton's treatment is more geometric than the modern approach, which emphasizes quaternions' algebraic properties.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] He founded a school of "quaternionists", and he tried to popularize quaternions in several books.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The last and longest of his books, *Elements of Quaternions*, was 800 pages long; it was edited by his son and published shortly after his death.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] After Hamilton's death, the Scottish mathematical physicist Peter Tait became the chief exponent of quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] At this time, quaternions were a mandatory examination topic in Dublin.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Topics in physics and geometry that would now be described using vectors, such as kinematics in space and Maxwell's equations, were described entirely in terms of quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] There was even a professional research association, the Quaternion Association, devoted to the study of quaternions and other hypercomplex number systems.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] From the mid-1880s, quaternions began to be displaced by vector analysis, which had been developed by Josiah Willard Gibbs, Oliver Heaviside, and Hermann von Helmholtz.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Vector analysis described the same phenomena as quaternions, so it borrowed some ideas and terminology liberally from the literature on quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] However, vector analysis was conceptually simpler and notationally cleaner, and eventually quaternions were relegated to a minor role in mathematics and physics.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A side-effect of this transition is that Hamilton's work is difficult to comprehend for many modern readers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Hamilton's original definitions are unfamiliar and his writing style was wordy and difficult to follow.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] However, quaternions have had a revival since the late 20th century, primarily due to their utility in describing spatial rotations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The representations of rotations by quaternions are more compact and quicker to compute than the representations by matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In addition, unlike Euler angles, they are not susceptible to "gimbal lock".
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] For this reason, quaternions are used in computer graphics, computer vision, robotics, nuclear magnetic resonance image sampling, control theory, signal processing, attitude control, physics, bioinformatics, molecular dynamics, computer simulations, and orbital mechanics.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] For example, it is common for the attitude control systems of spacecraft to be commanded in terms of quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Quaternions also have contributed to number theory, because of their relationships with the quadratic forms.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Hamilton had introduced biquaternions in his *Lectures on Quaternions*, and these were used by Ludwik Silberstein in 1914 to exhibit the Lorentz transformations of special relativity.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This representation of Lorentz transformations was also used by Cornelius Lanczos in 1949.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] As of 2018, their use has not yet overtaken rotation groups.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Clifford (1845 − 1879) introduced his algebras as a tensor product (”compound of algebras”) of quaternion algebras (and its even sub-algebra), a concept introduced by B.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Lipschitz (1832 − 1903) rediscovered independently the even subalgebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Moore (1876 − 1931) was to call Lipschitz’ algebras ”hyperquaternions”.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The term ”hyperquaternion” designates nowadays both the tensor product of n quaternion algebras $\mathbb {H} ^{\otimes n}$ and its even subalgebra $\mathbb {H} ^{\otimes n-1}\otimes \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Examples of hyperquaternions are: $\mathbb {H} ,\mathbb {H} ^{\otimes 2}=\mathbb {H} \otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {H}$ (isomorphic to the Clifford algebra $Cl_{3,1}\mathbb {(R)}$ and to $4\times 4$ real matrices $M(4,\mathbb {R} )$ ) leading to applications in special relativity.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Its even subalgebra is $\mathbb {H} \otimes \mathbb {C}$ (biquaternions).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Another example is $\mathbb {H} ^{\otimes 3}=M(4,\mathbb {H} )$ yielding a quaternionic matrix and its even subalgebra $\mathbb {H} ^{\otimes 2}\otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {C}$ (Dirac algebra).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] where a, b, c, d, are real numbers, and **i**, **j**, **k**, are symbols that can be interpreted as unit-vectors pointing along the three spatial axes.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In practice, if one of a, b, c, d is 0, the corresponding term is omitted; if a, b, c, d are all zero, the quaternion is the *zero quaternion*, denoted 0; if one of b, c, d equals 1, the corresponding term is written simply **i**, **j**, or **k**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A quaternion $q=a+b\,\mathbf {i} +c\,\mathbf {j} +d\,\mathbf {k}$ , can be decomposed into its *scalar part* ⁠ a ⁠ (sometimes *real part*) and its *vector part* $q-a=b\,\mathbf {i} +c\,\mathbf {j} +d\,\mathbf {k}$ (sometimes *imaginary part*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A quaternion that equals its real part (that is, its vector part is zero) is called a **scalar quaternion** (sometimes *real quaternion* or simply *scalar*), and is identified with the corresponding real number.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] That is, the real numbers are *embedded* in the quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A quaternion that equals its vector part is called a **vector quaternion** (sometimes *right quaternion*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Thus the quaternions form a division algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The *center* of a noncommutative ring is the subring of elements c such that *cx* = *xc* for every x.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The center of the quaternion algebra is the subfield of scalar quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In fact, it is a part of the definition that the scalar quaternions belong to the center.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A similar computation with **j** instead of **i** shows that one has also *b* = 0.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The quaternions form a division algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This means that the non-commutativity of multiplication is the only property that makes quaternions different from a field.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This non-commutativity has some unexpected consequences, among them that a polynomial equation over the quaternions can have more distinct solutions than the degree of the polynomial.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] For example, the equation *z*2 + 1 = 0, has infinitely many quaternion solutions, which are the quaternions *z* = *b* **i** + *c* **j** + *d* **k** such that *b*2 + *c*2 + *d*2 = 1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Thus these imaginary units form a unit sphere in the three-dimensional space of quaternion vectors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The distributive law makes it possible to expand the product so that it is a sum of products of basis elements.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Even though every quaternion can be viewed as a vector in a four-dimensional vector space, it is common to refer to the vector part as vectors in three-dimensional space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Hamilton also called vector quaternions *right quaternions* and real numbers (considered as quaternions with zero vector part) *scalar quaternions*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] where " ${}\cdot {}$ " and " $\times$ " denote respectively the dot product and the cross product.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Conjugation of quaternions is analogous to conjugation of complex numbers and to transposition (also known as reversal) of elements of Clifford algebras.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] To define it, let $q=a+b\,\mathbf {i} +c\,\mathbf {j} +d\,\mathbf {k}$ be a quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Conjugation is an involution, meaning that it is its own inverse, so conjugating an element twice returns the original element.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The conjugate of a product of two quaternions is the product of the conjugates *in the reverse order*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Conjugation can be used to extract the scalar and vector parts of a quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The square root of the product of a quaternion with its conjugate is called its *norm* and is denoted ‖*q*‖ (Hamilton called this quantity the *tensor* of *q*, but this conflicts with the modern meaning of "tensor").
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This is always a non-negative real number, and it is the same as the Euclidean norm on $\mathbb {H}$ considered as the vector space $\mathbb {R} ^{4}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Multiplying a quaternion by a real number scales its norm by the absolute value of the number.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Multiplicativity is a consequence of the formula for the conjugate of a product.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] (where i denotes the usual imaginary unit) and hence from the multiplicative property of determinants of square matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This makes $\mathbb {H}$ a metric space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Addition and multiplication are continuous in regard to the associated metric topology.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This follows with exactly the same proof as for the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ from the fact that $\mathbb {H}$ is a normed algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A **unit quaternion** is a quaternion of norm one.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Every nonzero quaternion has a unique polar decomposition $q=\lVert q\rVert \cdot \mathbf {U} q,$ while the zero quaternion can be formed from any unit quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Using conjugation and the norm makes it possible to define the reciprocal of a nonzero quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The product of a quaternion with its reciprocal should equal 1, and the considerations above imply that the product of q and $q^{*}/\left\Vert q\right\|^{2}$ is 1 (for either order of multiplication).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Since the multiplication is non-commutative, the quotient quantities *p q*−1 or *q*−1*p* are different (except if p and q have parallel vector parts): the notation ⁠*p*/*q*⁠ is ambiguous and should not be used.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The set $\mathbb {H}$ of all quaternions is a vector space over the real numbers with dimension 4.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Multiplication of quaternions is associative and distributive over vector addition, but it is not commutative.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Therefore, the quaternions, $\mathbb {H} ,$ are a non-commutative, associative algebra over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Even though $\mathbb {H}$ embeds multiple *copies* of the complex numbers, it is not itself an *associative algebra* over the complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Because it is possible to divide quaternions, they form a division algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This is a structure similar to a field except that it admits non-commutative multiplication.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] *Finite-dimensional associative division algebras* over the real numbers are very rare: The Frobenius theorem states that there are exactly three.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The quaternions are also an example of a composition algebra and of a unital Banach algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Because the product of any two basis vectors is plus or minus another basis vector, the set {±1, ±**i**, ±**j**, ±**k**} forms a group under multiplication.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This non-abelian group is called the quaternion group and is denoted Q8.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Here the first term in each of the sums is one of the basis elements 1, **i**, **j**, and **k**, and the second term is one of basis elements −1, −**i**, −**j**, and −**k**, not the additive inverses of 1, **i**, **j**, and **k**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A useful application of quaternions has been to interpolate the orientations of key-frames in computer graphics.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] For this reason, conjugation is sometimes called the *spatial inverse*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This is equal to the scalar parts of the products *pq*∗, *qp*∗, *p*∗*q*, and *q*∗*p*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Note that their vector parts are different.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] (Recall that the orientation is necessary to determine the sign.) This is equal to the vector part of the product *pq* (as quaternions), as well as the vector part of −*q*∗*p*∗.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] where *p*s and *q*s are the scalar parts, and *p*v and *q*v are the vector parts of p and q.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This shows that the noncommutativity of quaternion multiplication comes from the multiplication of vector quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] It also shows that two quaternions commute if and only if their vector parts are collinear.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Hamilton showed that this product computes the third vertex of a spherical triangle from two given vertices and their associated arc-lengths, which is also an algebra of points in Elliptic geometry.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Unit quaternions can be identified with rotations in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ and were called versors by Hamilton.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Also see Quaternions and spatial rotation for more information about modeling three-dimensional rotations using quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] See Hanson (2005) for visualization of quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Just as complex numbers can be represented as matrices, so can quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] There are at least two ways of representing quaternions as matrices in such a way that quaternion addition and multiplication correspond to matrix addition and matrix multiplication.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] One is to use 2 × 2 complex matrices, and the other is to use 4 × 4 real matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In each case, the representation given is one of a family of linearly related representations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] These are injective homomorphisms from $\mathbb {H}$ to the matrix rings M(2,**C**) and M(4,**R**), respectively.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] However, the representation of quaternions in M(4,ℝ) is not unique.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] There are 48 distinct matrix representations of this form, in which one of the matrices represents the scalar part and the other three are all skew-symmetric.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] More precisely, there are 48 sets of quadruples of matrices with these symmetry constraints, such that a function sending 1, **i**, **j**, and **k** to the matrices in the quadruple is a homomorphism, that is, it sends sums and products of quaternions to sums and products of matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In this representation, the conjugate of a quaternion corresponds to the transpose of the matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The fourth power of the norm of a quaternion is the determinant of the corresponding matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The scalar part of a quaternion is one quarter of the matrix trace.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] As with the 2 × 2 complex representation above, complex numbers can again be produced by constraining the coefficients suitably; for example, as block diagonal matrices with two 2 × 2 blocks by setting *c* = *d* = 0 .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Each 4 × 4 matrix representation of quaternions corresponds to a multiplication table of unit quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Then, the second column can be chosen to be either positive or negative, the third column can be chosen to be positive or negative, and the fourth column can be chosen to be positive or negative, giving 8 possibilities for the sign.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Multiplying the possibilities for the letter positions and for their signs yields 48.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Then replacing 1 with a, **i** with b, **j** with c, and **k** with d and removing the row and column headers yields a matrix representation of *a* + *b* **i** + *c* **j** + *d* **k** .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Quaternions are also used in one of the proofs of Lagrange's four-square theorem in number theory, which states that every nonnegative integer is the sum of four integer squares.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] As well as being an elegant theorem in its own right, Lagrange's four square theorem has useful applications in areas of mathematics outside number theory, such as combinatorial design theory.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The quaternion-based proof uses Hurwitz quaternions, a subring of the ring of all quaternions for which there is an analog of the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Quaternions can be represented as pairs of complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] From this perspective, quaternions are the result of applying the Cayley–Dickson construction to the complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This is a generalization of the construction of the complex numbers as pairs of real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Let $\mathbb {C} ^{2}$ be a two-dimensional vector space over the complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Choose a basis consisting of two elements 1 and **j**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] If we define **j**2 = −1 and *i* **j** = −**j** *i*, then we can multiply two vectors using the distributive law.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Using **k** as an abbreviated notation for the product *i* **j** leads to the same rules for multiplication as the usual quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Therefore, the above vector of complex numbers corresponds to the quaternion *a* + *b i* + *c* **j** + *d* **k**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In the complex numbers, $\mathbb {C} ,$ there are exactly two numbers, i and −*i*, that give −1 when squared.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In $\mathbb {H}$ there are infinitely many square roots of minus one: the quaternion solution for the square root of −1 is the unit sphere in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}.$ To see this, let *q* = *a* + *b* **i** + *c* **j** + *d* **k** be a quaternion, and assume that its square is −1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] To satisfy the last three equations, either *a* = 0 or b, c, and d are all 0 .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The latter is impossible because *a* is a real number and the first equation would imply that *a*2 = −1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] In other words: A quaternion squares to −1 if and only if it is a vector quaternion with norm 1 .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] By definition, the set of all such vectors forms the unit sphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Only negative real quaternions have infinitely many square roots.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] All others have just two (or one in the case of 0).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Each antipodal pair of square roots of −1 creates a distinct copy of the complex numbers inside the quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] This is an injective ring homomorphism from $\mathbb {C}$ to $\mathbb {H} ,$ which defines a field isomorphism from $\mathbb {C}$ onto its image.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The images of the embeddings corresponding to +q and −q are identical.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] (This is not the same as $q_{s}+\lVert q\rVert \cdot \mathbf {U} q.$ ) The versor of the vector part of q, $\mathbf {U} {\vec {q}}_{v},$ is a right versor with –1 as its square.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A straightforward verification shows that $a+bi\mapsto a+b\mathbf {U} {\vec {q}}_{v}$ defines an injective homomorphism of normed algebras from $\mathbb {C}$ into the quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] As $\mathbb {H}$ is the union of the images of all these homomorphisms, one can view the quaternions as a pencil of planes intersecting on the real line.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Each of these complex planes contains exactly one pair of antipodal points of the sphere of square roots of minus one.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The relationship of quaternions to each other within the complex subplanes of $\mathbb {H}$ can also be identified and expressed in terms of commutative subrings.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Specifically, since two quaternions p and q commute (i.e., *p q* = *q p*) only if they lie in the same complex subplane of $\mathbb {H} ,$ the profile of $\mathbb {H}$ as a union of complex planes arises when one seeks to find all commutative subrings of the quaternion ring.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Like functions of a complex variable, functions of a quaternion variable suggest useful physical models.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] For example, the original electric and magnetic fields described by Maxwell were functions of a quaternion variable.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Examples of other functions include the extension of the Mandelbrot set and Julia sets into 4-dimensional space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] A function of a quaternion can be defined from a power series with real coefficients.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] and amounts to the absolute value of half the angle subtended by p and q along a great arc of the S3 sphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The word "conjugation", besides the meaning given above, can also mean taking an element a to *r a r*−1 where r is some nonzero quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] All elements that are conjugate to a given element (in this sense of the word conjugate) have the same real part and the same norm of the vector part.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Thus the multiplicative group of nonzero quaternions acts by conjugation on the copy of $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ consisting of quaternions with real part equal to zero.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Conjugation by a unit quaternion (a quaternion of absolute value 1) with real part cos(*φ*) is a rotation by an angle 2*φ*, the axis of the rotation being the direction of the vector part.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The image of a subgroup of versors is a point group, and conversely, the preimage of a point group is a subgroup of versors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The preimage of a finite point group is called by the same name, with the prefix **binary**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] For instance, the preimage of the icosahedral group is the binary icosahedral group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The versors' group is isomorphic to SU(2), the group of complex unitary 2 × 2 matrices of determinant 1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Let A be the set of quaternions of the form *a* + *b* **i** + *c* **j** + *d* **k** where a, b, c, and d are either all integers or all half-integers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The set A is a ring (in fact a domain) and a lattice and is called the ring of Hurwitz quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] There are 24 unit quaternions in this ring, and they are the vertices of a regular 24 cell with Schläfli symbol {3,4,3} .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] They correspond to the double cover of the rotational symmetry group of the regular tetrahedron.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Similarly, the vertices of a regular 600 cell with Schläfli symbol {3,3,5} can be taken as the unit icosians, corresponding to the double cover of the rotational symmetry group of the regular icosahedron.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The double cover of the rotational symmetry group of the regular octahedron corresponds to the quaternions that represent the vertices of the disphenoidal 288-cell.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] The Quaternions can be generalized into further algebras called *quaternion algebras*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Take F to be any field with characteristic different from 2, and a and b to be elements of F; a four-dimensional unitary associative algebra can be defined over F with basis 1, **i**, **j**, and **i j**, where **i**2 = *a*, **j**2 = *b* and **i j** = −**j i** (so **(i j)**2 = −*a b*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p01] Quaternion algebras are isomorphic to the algebra of 2×2 matrices over F or form division algebras over F, depending on the choice of a and b.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] corresponds to a rotation of 180° in the plane containing *σ*1 and *σ*2.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] Indeed, the two structures $\operatorname {Cl} _{3,0}^{+}(\mathbb {R} )$ and $\mathbb {H}$ are isomorphic.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] In this picture, so-called "vector quaternions" (that is, pure imaginary quaternions) correspond not to vectors but to bivectors – quantities with magnitudes and orientations associated with particular 2D *planes* rather than 1D *directions*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] The relation to complex numbers becomes clearer, too: in 2D, with two vector directions *σ*1 and *σ*2, there is only one bivector basis element *σ*1*σ*2, so only one imaginary.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] But in 3D, with three vector directions, there are three bivector basis elements *σ*2*σ*3, *σ*3*σ*1, *σ*1*σ*2, so three imaginaries.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] In the Clifford algebra $\operatorname {Cl} _{4,0}(\mathbb {R} ),$ there are six bivector basis elements, since with four different basic vector directions, six different pairs and therefore six different linearly independent planes can be defined.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] Rotations in such spaces using these generalisations of quaternions, called rotors, can be very useful for applications involving homogeneous coordinates.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] But it is only in 3D that the number of basis bivectors equals the number of basis vectors, and each bivector can be identified as a pseudovector.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] For further detail about the geometrical uses of Clifford algebras, see Geometric algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] The quaternions are "essentially" the only (non-trivial) central simple algebra (CSA) over the real numbers, in the sense that every CSA over the real numbers is Brauer equivalent to either the real numbers or the quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] Explicitly, the Brauer group of the real numbers consists of two classes, represented by the real numbers and the quaternions, where the Brauer group is the set of all CSAs, up to equivalence relation of one CSA being a matrix ring over another.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] By the Artin–Wedderburn theorem (specifically, Wedderburn's part), CSAs are all matrix algebras over a division algebra, and thus the quaternions are the only non-trivial division algebra over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] CSAs – finite dimensional rings over a field, which are simple algebras (have no non-trivial 2-sided ideals, just as with fields) whose center is exactly the field – are a noncommutative analog of extension fields, and are more restrictive than general ring extensions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternion-p02] The fact that the quaternions are the only non-trivial CSA over the real numbers (up to equivalence) may be compared with the fact that the complex numbers are the only non-trivial finite field extension of the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Unit quaternions, known as *versors*, provide a convenient mathematical notation for representing spatial orientations and rotations of elements in three dimensional space (*3D rotations*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This is a generalization of the use of unit complex numbers for 2D rotations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Specifically, quaternions encode information about an axis-angle rotation about an arbitrary axis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Rotation and orientation quaternions have applications in computer graphics, computer vision, robotics, navigation, molecular dynamics, flight dynamics, orbital mechanics of satellites, and crystallographic texture analysis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] When used to represent rotation, unit quaternions are also called **rotation quaternions** as they represent the 3D rotation group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] When used to represent an orientation or attitude (body rotation relative to a reference coordinate system), they are called **orientation quaternions** or **attitude quaternions**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] A spatial rotation in the amount of $\theta$ radians about a fixed unit axis $(X,Y,Z)$ that denotes the *Euler axis* is given by the quaternion $(C,X\,S,Y\,S,Z\,S)$ , where $C=\cos(\theta /2)$ and $S=\sin(\theta /2)$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Compared to rotation matrices, quaternions are more compact, efficient, and numerically stable.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Compared to Euler angles, they are simpler to compose.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] However, they are not as intuitive and easy to understand and, due to the periodic nature of sine and cosine, rotation angles differing precisely by the natural period will be encoded into identical quaternions and recovered angles in radians will be limited to $[0,2\pi ]$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] In 3-dimensional space, according to Euler's rotation theorem, any rotation or sequence of rotations of a rigid body or coordinate system about a fixed point is equivalent to a single rotation by a given angle $\theta$ about a fixed axis (called the *Euler axis*) that runs through the fixed point.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The Euler axis is typically represented by a unit vector ${\vec {u}}$ ( ${\hat {e}}$ in the picture).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Therefore, any rotation in three dimensions can be represented as a vector ${\vec {u}}$ and an angle $\theta$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Quaternions give a simple way to encode this axis–angle representation using four real numbers, and can be used to apply (calculate) the corresponding rotation to a position vector (x,y,z), representing a point relative to the origin in **R**3.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] can be represented by conjugation by a unit quaternion **q**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] using the Hamilton product, where the vector part of the pure quaternion L(**p**′) = (0, *r**x*, *r**y*, *r**z*) is the new position vector of the point after the rotation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] In a programmatic implementation, the conjugation is achieved by constructing a pure quaternion whose vector part is **p**, and then performing the quaternion conjugation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The vector part of the resulting pure quaternion is the desired vector **r**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Clearly, L provides a linear transformation of the quaternion space to itself; also, since $\mathbf {q}$ is unitary, the transformation is an isometry.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Also, $L(\mathbf {q} )=\mathbf {q}$ and so L leaves vectors parallel to $\mathbf {q}$ invariant.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] So let $\mathbf {n}$ be the component of $\mathbf {p}$ orthogonal to the vector part of $\mathbf {q}$ and let $\mathbf {n} _{T}=\mathbf {u} \times \mathbf {n}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] A geometric fact independent of quaternions is the existence of a two-to-one mapping from physical rotations to rotational transformation matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] If 0 ⩽ $\theta$ ⩽ $2\pi$ , a physical rotation about ${\vec {u}}$ by $\theta$ and a physical rotation about $-{\vec {u}}$ by $2\pi -\theta$ both achieve the same final orientation by disjoint paths through intermediate orientations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] By inserting those vectors and angles into the formula for **q** above, one finds that if **q** represents the first rotation, −**q** represents the second rotation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This is a geometric proof that conjugation by **q** and by −**q** must produce the same rotational transformation matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] That fact is confirmed algebraically by noting that the conjugation is quadratic in **q**, so the sign of **q** cancels, and does not affect the result.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] (See 2:1 mapping of SU(2) to SO(3)) If both rotations are a half-turn $(\theta =\pi )$ , both **q** and −**q** will have a real coordinate equal to zero.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Otherwise, one will have a positive real part, representing a rotation by an angle less than $\pi$ , and the other will have a negative real part, representing a rotation by an angle greater than $\pi$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Mathematically, this operation carries the *set* of all "pure" quaternions **p** (those with real part equal to zero)—which constitute a 3-dimensional space among the quaternions—into itself, by the desired rotation about the axis ***u***, by the angle θ.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] (Each real quaternion is carried into itself by this operation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The rotation is clockwise if our line of sight points in the same direction as ${\vec {u}}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] which is the same as rotating (conjugating) by **q** and then by **p**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The scalar component of the result is necessarily zero.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The quaternion inverse of a rotation is the opposite rotation, since $\mathbf {q} ^{-1}(\mathbf {q} {\vec {v}}\mathbf {q} ^{-1})\mathbf {q} ={\vec {v}}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The square of a quaternion rotation is a rotation by twice the angle around the same axis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] More generally **q***n* is a rotation by n times the angle around the same axis as **q**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This can be extended to arbitrary real n, allowing for smooth interpolation between spatial orientations; see Slerp.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] in which **q**′ corresponds to the rotation **q**1 followed by the rotation **q**2.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Thus, an arbitrary number of rotations can be composed together and then applied as a single rotation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Consider the rotation f around the axis ${\vec {v}}=\mathbf {i} +\mathbf {j} +\mathbf {k}$ , with a rotation angle of 120°, or ⁠2π/3⁠ radians.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] It can be proven that the inverse of a unit quaternion is obtained simply by changing the sign of its imaginary components.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] As expected, the rotation corresponds to keeping a cube held fixed at one point, and rotating it 120° about the long diagonal through the fixed point (observe how the three axes are permuted cyclically).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This can be obtained by using vector calculus and linear algebra if we express $\mathbf {p}$ and $\mathbf {q}$ as scalar and vector parts and use the formula for the multiplication operation in the equation $\mathbf {p'} =\mathbf {q} \mathbf {p} \mathbf {q} ^{-1}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] where $\otimes$ denotes the outer product, $\mathbf {I}$ is the identity matrix and $[\mathbf {v} ]_{\times }$ is the transformation matrix that when multiplied from the right with a vector $\mathbf {u}$ gives the cross product $\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {u}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Since $\mathbf {p} '=\mathbf {R} \mathbf {p}$ , we can identify $\mathbf {R}$ as $s\left(\mathbf {v} \otimes \mathbf {v} +q_{r}^{2}\mathbf {I} +2q_{r}[\mathbf {v} ]_{\times }+[\mathbf {v} ]_{\times }^{2}\right)$ , which upon expansion should result in the expression written in matrix form above.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] where $\operatorname {atan2}$ is the two-argument arctangent.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] While $\theta =2\operatorname {acos} (q_{r})$ works, it is numerically unstable (inaccurate) near $q_{r}=\pm 1$ for numbers with finite precision.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Care should be taken when the quaternion approaches a scalar, since due to degeneracy the axis of an identity rotation is not well-defined.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] A benefit of the quaternion formulation of the composition of two rotations *R**B* and *R**A* is that it yields directly the rotation axis and angle of the composite rotation *R**C* = *R**B**R**A*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Let the quaternion associated with a spatial rotation R be constructed from its rotation axis **S** with the rotation angle $\varphi$ around this axis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This is Rodrigues' formula for the axis of a composite rotation defined in terms of the axes of the two rotations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] He derived this formula in 1840 (see page 408).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The three rotation axes **A**, **B**, and **C** form a spherical triangle and the dihedral angles between the planes formed by the sides of this triangle are defined by the rotation angles.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Hamilton presented the component form of these equations showing that the quaternion product computes the third vertex of a spherical triangle from two given vertices and their associated arc-lengths, which is also defines an algebra for points in Elliptic geometry.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The normalized rotation axis, removing the ${\textstyle \cos {\frac {\gamma }{2}}}$ from the expanded product, leaves the vector which is the rotation axis, times some constant.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Care should be taken normalizing the axis vector when $\gamma$ is 0 or $k2\pi$ where the vector is near 0 ; which is identity, or 0 rotation around any axis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The rotated quaternion **p' = q p q**−1 needs to be differentiated with respect to the rotating quaternion **q**, when the rotation is estimated from numerical optimization.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The estimation of rotation angle is an essential procedure in 3D object registration or camera calibration.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The complex numbers can be defined by introducing an abstract symbol **i** which satisfies the usual rules of algebra and additionally the rule **i**2 = −1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] From this all of the rules of quaternion arithmetic follow, such as the rules on multiplication of quaternion basis elements.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The imaginary part $b\mathbf {i} +c\mathbf {j} +d\mathbf {k}$ of a quaternion behaves like a vector ${\vec {v}}=(b,c,d)$ in three-dimensional vector space, and the real part a behaves like a scalar in **R**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Some might find it strange to add a *number* to a *vector*, as they are objects of very different natures, or to *multiply* two vectors together, as this operation is usually undefined.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] However, if one remembers that it is a mere notation for the real and imaginary parts of a quaternion, it becomes more legitimate.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] We can express quaternion multiplication in the modern language of vector cross and dot products (which were actually inspired by the quaternions in the first place).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Quaternion multiplication is noncommutative (because of the cross product, which anti-commutes), while scalar–scalar and scalar–vector multiplications commute.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] as can be verified by direct calculation (note the similarity to the multiplicative inverse of complex numbers).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] yields the vector ${\vec {v}}$ rotated by an angle $\alpha$ around the axis ${\vec {u}}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This is the formula of a rotation by $\alpha$ around the *u*→ axis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] A very formal explanation of the properties used in this section is given by Altman.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Unit quaternions represent the group of Euclidean rotations in three dimensions in a very straightforward way.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The correspondence between rotations and quaternions can be understood by first visualizing the space of rotations itself.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] In order to visualize the space of rotations, it helps to consider a simpler case.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Any rotation in three dimensions can be described by a rotation by some angle about some axis; for our purposes, we will use an axis *vector* to establish handedness for our angle.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Consider the special case in which the axis of rotation lies in the *xy* plane.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] We can then specify the axis of one of these rotations by a point on a circle through which the vector crosses, and we can select the radius of the circle to denote the angle of rotation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Similarly, a rotation whose axis of rotation lies in the *xy* plane can be described as a point on a sphere of *fixed* radius in *three* dimensions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Beginning at the north pole of a sphere in three-dimensional space, we specify the point at the north pole to be the identity rotation (a zero angle rotation).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Just as in the case of the identity rotation, no axis of rotation is defined, and the angle of rotation (zero) is irrelevant.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] A rotation having a very small rotation angle can be specified by a slice through the sphere parallel to the *xy* plane and very near the north pole.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The circle defined by this slice will be very small, corresponding to the small angle of the rotation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] As the rotation angles become larger, the slice moves in the negative z direction, and the circles become larger until the equator of the sphere is reached, which will correspond to a rotation angle of 180 degrees.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Continuing southward, the radii of the circles now become smaller (corresponding to the absolute value of the angle of the rotation considered as a negative number).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Finally, as the south pole is reached, the circles shrink once more to the identity rotation, which is also specified as the point at the south pole.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Notice that a number of characteristics of such rotations and their representations can be seen by this visualization.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The space of rotations is continuous, each rotation has a neighborhood of rotations which are nearly the same, and this neighborhood becomes flat as the neighborhood shrinks.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Also, each rotation is actually represented by two antipodal points on the sphere, which are at opposite ends of a line through the center of the sphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This reflects the fact that each rotation can be represented as a rotation about some axis, or, equivalently, as a negative rotation about an axis pointing in the opposite direction (a so-called double cover).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The "latitude" of a circle representing a particular rotation angle will be half of the angle represented by that rotation, since as the point is moved from the north to south pole, the latitude ranges from zero to 180 degrees, while the angle of rotation ranges from 0 to 360 degrees.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] (the "longitude" of a point then represents a particular axis of rotation.) Note however that this set of rotations is not closed under composition.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Two successive rotations with axes in the *xy* plane will not necessarily give a rotation whose axis lies in the *xy* plane, and thus cannot be represented as a point on the sphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This will not be the case with a general rotation in 3-space, in which rotations do form a closed set under composition.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This visualization can be extended to a general rotation in 3-dimensional space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The identity rotation is a point, and a small angle of rotation about some axis can be represented as a point on a sphere with a small radius.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] As the angle of rotation grows, the sphere grows, until the angle of rotation reaches 180 degrees, at which point the sphere begins to shrink, becoming a point as the angle approaches 360 degrees (or zero degrees from the negative direction).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This set of expanding and contracting spheres represents a hypersphere in four dimensional space (a 3-sphere).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Just as in the simpler example above, each rotation represented as a point on the hypersphere is matched by its antipodal point on that hypersphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The "latitude" on the hypersphere will be half of the corresponding angle of rotation, and the neighborhood of any point will become "flatter" (i.e. be represented by a 3-D Euclidean space of points) as the neighborhood shrinks.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This behavior is matched by the set of unit quaternions: A general quaternion represents a point in a four dimensional space, but constraining it to have unit magnitude yields a three-dimensional space equivalent to the surface of a hypersphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The magnitude of the unit quaternion will be unity, corresponding to a hypersphere of unit radius.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The vector part of a unit quaternion represents the radius of the 2-sphere corresponding to the axis of rotation, and its magnitude is the sine of half the angle of rotation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Each rotation is represented by two unit quaternions of opposite sign, and, as in the space of rotations in three dimensions, the quaternion product of two unit quaternions will yield a unit quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Also, the space of unit quaternions is "flat" in any infinitesimal neighborhood of a given unit quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] We can parameterize the surface of a sphere with two coordinates, such as latitude and longitude.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] But latitude and longitude are ill-behaved (degenerate as described by the hairy ball theorem) at the north and south poles, though the poles are not intrinsically different from any other points on the sphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] At the poles (latitudes +90° and −90°), the longitude becomes meaningless.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] It can be shown that no two-parameter coordinate system can avoid such degeneracy.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] We can avoid such problems by embedding the sphere in three-dimensional space and parameterizing it with three Cartesian coordinates (*w*, *x*, *y*), placing the north pole at (*w*, *x*, *y*) = (1, 0, 0), the south pole at (*w*, *x*, *y*) = (−1, 0, 0), and the equator at *w* = 0, *x*2 + *y*2 = 1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Points on the sphere satisfy the constraint *w*2 + *x*2 + *y*2 = 1, so we still have just two degrees of freedom though there are three coordinates.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] A point (*w*, *x*, *y*) on the sphere represents a rotation in the ordinary space around the horizontal axis directed by the vector (*x*, *y*, 0) by an angle $\alpha =2\cos ^{-1}w=2\sin ^{-1}{\sqrt {x^{2}+y^{2}}}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] In the same way the hyperspherical space of 3D rotations can be parameterized by three angles (Euler angles), but any such parameterization is degenerate at some points on the hypersphere, leading to the problem of gimbal lock.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] We can avoid this by using four Euclidean coordinates *w*, *x*, *y*, *z*, with *w*2 + *x*2 + *y*2 + *z*2 = 1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The multiplication of quaternions is non-commutative.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This fact explains how the **p** ↦ **q p q**−1 formula can work at all, having **q q**−1 = 1 by definition.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Since the multiplication of unit quaternions corresponds to the composition of three-dimensional rotations, this property can be made intuitive by showing that three-dimensional rotations are not commutative in general.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] The figure to the right illustrates this with dice.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Use the right hand to create a pair of 90 degree rotations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Alternatively, set two books next to each other.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Rotate one of them 90 degrees clockwise around the z axis, then flip it 180 degrees around the x axis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Take the other book, flip it 180° around x axis first, and 90° clockwise around z later.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This shows that, in general, the composition of two different rotations around two distinct spatial axes will not commute.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] Alternatively, the dependence on orientation is expressed in referring to such ${\vec {u}}$ that specifies a rotation as to *axial vectors*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] In quaternionic formalism the choice of an orientation of the space corresponds to order of multiplication: **ij** = **k** but **ji** = −**k**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] If one reverses the orientation, then the formula above becomes **p** ↦ **q**−1 **p q**, i.e., a unit **q** is replaced with the conjugate quaternion – the same behaviour as of axial vectors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] It is reported that the existence and continued usage of an alternative quaternion convention in the aerospace and, to a lesser extent, robotics community is incurring a *significant and ongoing cost* [*sic*].
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] This convention is also referred to as "JPL convention" for its use in some parts of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] To identify the changes under Shuster's convention, see that the sign before the cross product is flipped from plus to minus.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p01] which is exactly the transpose of the rotation matrix converted under the traditional convention.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] The representation of a rotation as a quaternion (4 numbers) is more compact than the representation as an orthogonal matrix (9 numbers).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Furthermore, for a given axis and angle, one can easily construct the corresponding quaternion, and conversely, for a given quaternion one can easily read off the axis and the angle.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Both of these are much harder with matrices or Euler angles.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] In video games and other applications, one is often interested in "smooth rotations", meaning that the scene should slowly rotate and not in a single step.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] This can be accomplished by choosing a curve such as the spherical linear interpolation in the quaternions, with one endpoint being the identity transformation 1 (or some other initial rotation) and the other being the intended final rotation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] This is more problematic with other representations of rotations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] When composing several rotations on a computer, rounding errors necessarily accumulate.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] A quaternion that is slightly off still represents a rotation after being normalized: a matrix that is slightly off may not be orthogonal any more and is harder to convert back to a proper orthogonal matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Quaternions also avoid a phenomenon called gimbal lock which can result when, for example in pitch/yaw/roll rotational systems, the pitch is rotated 90° up or down, so that yaw and roll then correspond to the same motion, and a degree of freedom of rotation is lost.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] In a gimbal-based aerospace inertial navigation system, for instance, this could have disastrous results if the aircraft is in a steep dive or ascent.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] This rotation matrix is used on vector w as $w_{\text{rotated}}=R\cdot w$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] where the order a, b is important since the cross product of two vectors is not commutative.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] One must be careful when converting a rotation matrix to a quaternion, as several straightforward methods tend to be unstable when the trace (sum of the diagonal elements) of the rotation matrix is zero or very small.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] For a stable method of converting an orthogonal matrix to a quaternion, see the Rotation matrix#Quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] The above section described how to recover a quaternion **q** from a 3 × 3 rotation matrix Q.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Suppose, however, that we have some matrix Q that is not a pure rotation—due to round-off errors, for example—and we wish to find the quaternion **q** that most accurately represents Q.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] and find the eigenvector (*x*, *y*, *z*, *w*) corresponding to the largest eigenvalue (that value will be 1 if and only if Q is a pure rotation).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] The quaternion so obtained will correspond to the rotation closest to the original matrix Q .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] This section discusses the performance implications of using quaternions versus other methods (axis/angle or rotation matrices) to perform rotations in 3D.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Only three of the quaternion components are independent, as a rotation is represented by a unit quaternion.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] For further calculation one usually needs all four elements, so all calculations would suffer additional expense from recovering the fourth component.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Likewise, angle–axis can be stored in a three-component vector by multiplying the unit direction by the angle (or a function thereof), but this comes at additional computational cost when using it for calculations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Similarly, a rotation matrix requires orthogonal basis vectors, so in 3D space the third vector can unambiguously be calculated from the first two vectors with a cross product (though there is ambiguity in the sign of the third vector if improper rotations are allowed).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] A rotation can be represented by a unit-length quaternion **q** = (*w*, *r*→) with scalar (real) part w and vector (imaginary) part *r*→.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] This requires only 15 multiplications and 15 additions to evaluate (or 18 multiplications and 12 additions if the factor of 2 is done via multiplication.) This formula, originally thought to be used with axis/angle notation (Rodrigues' formula), can also be applied to quaternion notation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] This yields the same result as the less efficient but more compact formula of quaternion multiplication ${\vec {v}}_{\text{new}}=q{\vec {v}}q^{-1}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Use the angle/axis formula to convert an angle/axis to a rotation matrix R then multiplying with a vector, or, similarly, use a formula to convert quaternion notation to a rotation matrix, then multiplying with a vector.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Converting the angle/axis to R costs 12 multiplications, 2 function calls (sin, cos), and 10 additions/subtractions; from item 1, rotating using R adds an additional 9 multiplications and 6 additions for a total of 21 multiplications, 16 add/subtractions, and 2 function calls (sin, cos).
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Converting a quaternion to R costs 12 multiplications and 12 additions/subtractions; from item 1, rotating using R adds an additional 9 multiplications and 6 additions for a total of 21 multiplications and 18 additions/subtractions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] where the matrices $M_{\rm {L}}$ and $M_{\rm {R}}$ represent left and right quaternion multiplications, respectively.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Together, these matrices form an isoclinic decomposition of a rotation in $\mathbb {R} ^{4}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Thus, the two matrices $M_{\rm {L}}$ and $M_{\rm {R}}$ must commute.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] This implies the existence of two commuting subgroups within the group of four-dimensional rotations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] An arbitrary four-dimensional rotation has six degrees of freedom, with each matrix contributing three of these six degrees of freedom.
[src:quaternions-octonions/quaternions-and-spatial-rotation-p02] Since the generators of the four-dimensional rotations can be represented by pairs of quaternions (as follows), all four-dimensional rotations can also be represented.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] In abstract algebra, the **split-quaternions** or **coquaternions** form an algebraic structure introduced by James Cockle in 1849 under the latter name.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] They form an associative algebra of dimension four over the real numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] After introduction in the 20th century of coordinate-free definitions of rings and algebras, it was proved that the algebra of split-quaternions is isomorphic to the ring of the 2×2 real matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] So the study of split-quaternions can be reduced to the study of real matrices, and this may explain why there are few mentions of split-quaternions in the mathematical literature of the 20th and 21st centuries.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The split-quaternions are also equivalent to the Clifford algebras Cl2,0(**R**) ≅ Cl1,1(**R**) over the real numbers, and so the study of split-quaternions is also subsumed in the study of Clifford algebra and geometric algebra in the mathematics and physics literature.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] So, the split-quaternions form a real vector space of dimension four with {1, i, j, k} as a basis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] They form also a noncommutative ring, by extending the above product rules by distributivity to all split-quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] satisfy the same multiplication table as the corresponding split-quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] As these matrices form a basis of the two-by-two matrices, the unique linear function that maps 1, i, j, k to ${\boldsymbol {1}},{\boldsymbol {i}},{\boldsymbol {j}},{\boldsymbol {k}}$ (respectively) induces an algebra isomorphism from the split-quaternions to the two-by-two real matrices.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The above multiplication rules imply that the eight elements 1, i, j, k, −1, −i, −j, −k form a group under this multiplication, which is isomorphic to the dihedral group D4, the symmetry group of a square.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] It fixes the vertices $\mathbf {x} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {x} _{3}$ and reflects the vertices $\mathbf {x} _{2}$ and $\mathbf {x} _{4}$ into each other.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The matrix ${\boldsymbol {k}}$ is a reflection about the x axis.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The negative of the identity matrix is the square of the matrix $\mathbf {i}$ , has determinant $+1$ , and rotates the square by 180° about the origin.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Like the quaternions introduced by Hamilton in 1843, they form a four dimensional real associative algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] But like the real algebra of 2×2 matrices – and unlike the real algebra of quaternions – the split-quaternions contain nontrivial zero divisors, nilpotent elements, and idempotents.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] (For example, ⁠1/2⁠(1 + j) is an idempotent zero-divisor, and i − j is nilpotent.) As an algebra over the real numbers, the algebra of split-quaternions is isomorphic to the algebra of 2×2 real matrices by the above defined isomorphism.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] This isomorphism allows identifying each split-quaternion with a 2×2 matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] So every property of split-quaternions corresponds to a similar property of matrices, which is often named differently.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] In term of matrices, the conjugate is the cofactor matrix obtained by exchanging the diagonal entries and changing the sign of the other two entries.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] which is called the *norm* of the split-quaternion or the determinant of the associated matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] It equals the trace of associated matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The norm of a product of two split-quaternions is the product of their norms.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Equivalently, the determinant of a product of matrices is the product of their determinants.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] This property means that split-quaternions form a composition algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] As there are nonzero split-quaternions having a zero norm, split-quaternions form a "split composition algebra" – hence their name.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] A split-quaternion with a nonzero norm has a multiplicative inverse, namely *q*∗/*N*(*q*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] In terms of matrices, this is equivalent to the Cramer rule that asserts that a matrix is invertible if and only its determinant is nonzero, and, in this case, the inverse of the matrix is the quotient of the adjugate matrix by the determinant.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The adjugate matrix is the transpose of the cofactor matrix and is also known as the adjoint or adjunct matrix.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Geometrically, the split-quaternions can be compared to Hamilton's quaternions as pencils of planes.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] In both cases the real numbers form the axis of a pencil.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] In Hamilton quaternions there is a sphere of imaginary units, and any pair of antipodal imaginary units generates a complex plane with the real line.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] For split-quaternions there are hyperboloids of hyperbolic and imaginary units that generate split-complex or ordinary complex planes, as described below in § Stratification.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] There is a representation of the split-quaternions as a unital associative subalgebra of the 2×2 matrices with complex entries.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Here, i (italic) is the imaginary unit, not to be confused with the split quaternion basis element i (upright roman).
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] where the superscript $^{*}$ denotes a complex conjugate.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The isomorphism of algebras is completed by use of matrix multiplication to verify the identities involving i, j, and k.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] It follows that for a split quaternion represented as a complex matrix, the conjugate is the matrix of the cofactors, and the norm is the determinant.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] With the representation of split quaternions as complex matrices, the matrices of determinant 1 form the special unitary group SU(1,1), which is used to describe hyperbolic motions of the Poincaré disk model in hyperbolic geometry.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Split-quaternions may be generated by modified Cayley–Dickson construction similar to the method of L.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Dickson and Adrian Albert. for the division algebras **C**, **H**, and **O**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The multiplication rule $(a,b)(c,d)\ =\ (ac+d^{*}b,\ da+bc^{*})$ is used when producing the doubled product in the real-split cases.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] In this section, the real subalgebras generated by a single split-quaternion are studied and classified.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] One has *q** = –*q*, and therefore $p^{2}=w^{2}+2wq-N(q).$ It follows that *p*2 is a real number if and only *p* is either a real number (*q* = 0 and *p* = *w*) or a *purely nonreal split quaternion* (*w* = 0 and *p* = *q*).
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The structure of the subalgebra $\mathbb {R} [p]$ generated by p follows straightforwardly.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Its dimension is two except if p is real (in this case, the subalgebra is simply $\mathbb {R}$ ).
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Three cases have to be considered, which are detailed in the next subsections.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] This is a parametrization of all split-quaternions whose nonreal part is nilpotent.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The algebra generated by a nilpotent element is isomorphic to $\mathbb {R} [X]/\langle X^{2}\rangle$ and to the plane of dual numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] This is a parametrization of all split-quaternions whose nonreal part has a positive norm.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The algebra generated by a split-quaternion with a nonreal part of positive norm is isomorphic to $\mathbb {R} [X]/\langle X^{2}+1\rangle$ and to the field $\mathbb {C}$ of complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] It follows that ⁠1/*n*⁠ *q* belongs to the hyperboloid of one sheet of equation *y*2 + *z*2 − *x*2 = 1.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] This is a parametrization of all split-quaternions whose nonreal part has a negative norm.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The algebra generated by a split-quaternion with a nonreal part of negative norm is isomorphic to $\mathbb {R} [X]/\langle X^{2}-1\rangle$ and to the ring of split-complex numbers.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] As seen above, the purely nonreal split-quaternions of norm –1, 1 and 0 form respectively a hyperboloid of one sheet, a hyperboloid of two sheets and a circular cone in the space of non real quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] These surfaces are pairwise asymptote and do not intersect.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] This stratification can be refined by considering split-quaternions of a fixed norm: for every real number *n* ≠ 0 the purely nonreal split-quaternions of norm *n* form an hyperboloid.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] All these hyperboloids are asymptote to the above cone, and none of these surfaces intersect any other.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] As the set of the purely nonreal split-quaternions is the disjoint union of these surfaces, this provides the desired stratification.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Split quaternions have been applied to colour balance The model refers to the Jordan algebra of symmetric matrices representing the algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The model reconciles trichromacy with Hering's opponency and uses the Cayley–Klein model of hyperbolic geometry for chromatic distances.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The coquaternions were initially introduced (under that name) in 1849 by James Cockle in the London–Edinburgh–Dublin Philosophical Magazine.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The introductory papers by Cockle were recalled in the 1904 *Bibliography* of the Quaternion Association.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Clifford nearly described representation of split-quaternions with matrices: He used *K* to express the imaginary unit ${\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\-1&0\end{pmatrix}}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Alexander Macfarlane called the structure of split-quaternion vectors an *exspherical system* when he was speaking at the International Congress of Mathematicians in Paris in 1900.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Macfarlane considered the "hyperboloidal counterpart to spherical analysis" in a 1910 article "Unification and Development of the Principles of the Algebra of Space" in the *Bulletin* of the Quaternion Association.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] Hans Beck compared split-quaternion transformations to the circle-permuting property of Möbius transformations in 1910.
[src:quaternions-octonions/split-quaternion] The split-quaternion structure has also been mentioned briefly in the *Annals of Mathematics*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] In mathematics, a **versor** is a quaternion whose norm is one, also known as a **unit quaternion**.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] where the condition $\ \mathbf {r} ^{2}=-1\$ means that $\ \mathbf {r} \$ is an algebraic imaginary unit.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] There is a sphere of imaginary units in the quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Note that the expression for a versor is just Euler's formula for the imaginary unit $\ \mathbf {r} ~.$ If $\ a={\tfrac {\pi }{2}}\$ (when $\ a\$ is a right angle), then $\ u=\mathbf {r} \ ,$ and it is called a *right versor*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The mapping $\ q\ \longmapsto \ u^{-1}q\ u\$ corresponds to 3-dimensional rotation, and has the angle $\ 2\ a\$ about the axis $\ \mathbf {r} \$ in axis–angle representation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The collection of versors, with quaternion multiplication, forms a group, and appears as a 3-sphere in the 4-dimensional quaternion algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] where $\ \mathbf {T} \ \!q\$ is Hamilton's notation for the norm of $\ q\$ (in modern notation $\ \mathbf {T} \ \!q=\|q\|$ ).
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The norm of a versor is always equal to one; hence they occupy the unit 3-sphere in $\ \mathbb {H} \$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Examples of versors include the eight elements of the quaternion group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Of particular importance are the right versors, which have angle $\ {\tfrac {\pi }{2}}~.$ These versors have zero scalar part, and so are vectors of length one (unit vectors).
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The right versors form a sphere of square roots of −1 in the quaternion algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The generators **i**, **j**, and **k** are examples of right versors, as well as their additive inverses.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Other versors include the twenty-four Hurwitz quaternions that have the norm 1 and form vertices of a 24-cell polychoron.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Hamilton defined a quaternion as the quotient of two vectors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] A versor can be defined as the quotient of two unit vectors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] For any fixed plane Π the quotient of two unit vectors lying in Π depends only on the angle (directed) between them, the same a as in the unit vector–angle representation of a versor explained above.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] That's why it may be natural to understand corresponding versors as directed arcs that connect pairs of unit vectors and lie on a great circle formed by intersection of Π with the unit sphere, where the plane Π passes through the origin.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Arcs of the same direction and length (or, the same, subtended angle in radians) are equipollent and correspond to the same versor.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Such an arc, although lying in the three-dimensional space, does not represent a path of a point rotating as described with the sandwiched product with the versor.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Indeed, it represents the left multiplication action of the versor on quaternions that preserves the plane Π and the corresponding great circle of 3-vectors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The 3-dimensional rotation defined by the versor has the angle two times the arc's subtended angle, and preserves the same plane.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] It is a rotation about the corresponding vector **r**, that is perpendicular to Π.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Multiplication of versors corresponds to the (non-commutative) "addition" of great circle arcs on the unit sphere.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Any pair of great circles either is the same circle or has two intersection points.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Hence, one can always move the point B and the corresponding vector to one of these points such that the beginning of the second arc will be the same as the end of the first arc.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The facility with which versors express elliptic geometry or rotations in 3-space is due to the parametric representation of the factors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Take a generic spherical triangle ABC with angles a, b, and c as the sides opposite the capital vertex.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] One uses unit vectors perpendicular to the plane of each side of the triangle, say r, s, and t .
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] each expanded by Euler's formula since each of the squares of r, s and t is minus one.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] the versor product corresponds to addition of spherical arcs.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The geometry of elliptic space has been described as the space of versors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The orthogonal group in three dimensions, rotation group SO(3), is frequently interpreted with versors via the inner automorphism $\ q\mapsto u^{-1}q\ u\$ where u is a versor.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The plane $\ \{\ x+y\ \mathbf {r} \ :\ (x,y)\in \mathbb {R} ^{2}\ \}\subset \mathbb {H} \$ is isomorphic to $\ \mathbb {C} \$ and the inner automorphism, by commutativity, reduces to the identity mapping there.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Since quaternions can be interpreted as an algebra of two complex dimensions, the rotation action can also be viewed through the special unitary group SU(2).
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] For a fixed **r**, versors of the form $\ \exp(a\ \mathbf {r} )\$ where $\ a\in \left(-\pi ,\pi \ \right]\ ,$ form a subgroup isomorphic to the circle group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Orbits of the left multiplication action of this subgroup are fibers of a fiber bundle over the 2-sphere, known as Hopf fibration in the case **r** = **i** ; other vectors give isomorphic, but not identical fibrations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Lyons (2003) gives an elementary introduction to quaternions to elucidate the Hopf fibration as a mapping on unit quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] He writes "the fibers of the Hopf map are circles in S3 ".
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Versors have been used to represent rotations of the Bloch sphere with quaternion multiplication.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The facility of versors illustrate elliptic geometry, in particular elliptic space, a three-dimensional realm of rotations.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The versors are the points of this elliptic space, though they refer to rotations in 4-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Given two fixed versors u and v, the mapping $\ q\mapsto u\ q\ v\$ is an *elliptic motion*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] If one of the fixed versors is 1, then the motion is a *Clifford translation* of the elliptic space, named after William Kingdon Clifford who was a proponent of the space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] An elliptic line through versor u is $\ \{\ u\ \exp(a\ \mathbf {r} )\ :\ 0\leq a<\pi \ \}~.$ Parallelism in the space is expressed by Clifford parallels.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The set of all versors, with their multiplication as quaternions, forms a continuous group *G*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] For a fixed pair $\ \{-\mathbf {r} ,+\mathbf {r} \ \}\$ of right versors, $\ G_{1}=\{\ \exp(a\ \mathbf {r} )\ :\ a\in \mathbb {R} \ \}\$ is a one-parameter subgroup that is isomorphic to the circle group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] As noted by Hurwitz, the 16 quaternions $\ {\tfrac {\ 1\ }{2}}\left(\pm \mathbf {1} \pm \mathbf {i} \pm \mathbf {j} \pm \mathbf {k} \right)\$ all have norm one, so they are in *G*.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Joined with Q8, these unit Hurwitz quaternions form a group *G*2 of order 24 called the binary tetrahedral group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The group elements, taken as points on S3, form a 24-cell.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] By a process of bitruncation of the 24-cell, the 48-cell on *G* is obtained, and these versors multiply as the binary octahedral group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Another subgroup is formed by 120 icosians which multiply in the manner of the binary icosahedral group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] A hyperbolic versor is a generalization of quaternionic versors to indefinite orthogonal groups, such as Lorentz group.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Such elements arise in split algebras, for example split-complex numbers or split-quaternions.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] It was the algebra of tessarines discovered by James Cockle in 1848 that first provided hyperbolic versors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] In fact, Cockle wrote the above equation (with **j** in place of **r**) when he found that the tessarines included the new type of imaginary element.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] This versor was used by Homersham Cox (1882/1883) in relation to quaternion multiplication.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The primary exponent of hyperbolic versors was Alexander Macfarlane, as he worked to shape quaternion theory to serve physical science.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] He saw the modelling power of hyperbolic versors operating on the split-complex number plane, and in 1891 he introduced hyperbolic quaternions to extend the concept to 4-space.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Problems in that algebra led to use of biquaternions after 1900.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] ... the root of a quadratic equation may be versor in nature or scalar in nature.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] If it is versor in nature, then the part affected by the radical involves the axis perpendicular to the plane of reference, and this is so, whether the radical involves the square root of minus one or not.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] In the former case the versor is circular, in the latter hyperbolic.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Today the concept of a one-parameter group subsumes the concepts of versor and hyperbolic versor as the terminology of Sophus Lie has replaced that of Hamilton and Macfarlane.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] In particular, for each **r** such that **r r** = +1 or **r r** = −1, the mapping $a\mapsto \exp(a\,\mathbf {r} )$ takes the real line to a group of hyperbolic or ordinary versors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] In the ordinary case, when **r** and **−r** are antipodes on a sphere, the one-parameter groups have the same points but are oppositely directed.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] In physics, this aspect of rotational symmetry is termed a doublet.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Robb (1911) defined the parameter *rapidity*, which specifies a change in frame of reference.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] This *rapidity* parameter corresponds to the real variable in a one-parameter group of hyperbolic versors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] With the further development of special relativity the action of a hyperbolic versor came to be called a Lorentz boost.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Sophus Lie was less than a year old when Hamilton first described quaternions, but Lie's name has become associated with all groups generated by exponentiation.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The set of versors with their multiplication has been denoted Sl(1,q) by Gilmore (1974).
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Sl(1,q) is the special linear group of one dimension over quaternions, the "special" indicating that all elements are of norm one.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The group is isomorphic to SU(2,c), a special unitary group, a frequently used designation since quaternions and versors are sometimes considered archaic for group theory.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The special orthogonal group SO(3,r) of rotations in three dimensions is closely related: it is a 2:1 homomorphic image of SU(2,c).
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The subspace $\ \{\ x\ \mathbf {i} +y\ \mathbf {j} +z\ \mathbf {k} ~:~x,\ y,\ z\in \mathbb {R} \ \}\subset \mathbb {H} \$ is called the Lie algebra of the group of versors.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The commutator $\ {\bigl [}\ u\ ,v\ {\bigr ]}\ \equiv \ u\ v-v\ u\ ,$ is double the cross product of two vectors, which forms the multiplication operation in the Lie algebra.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The close relation to SU(1,c) and SO(3,r) is evident in the isomorphism of their Lie algebras.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Lie groups that contain hyperbolic versors include the group on the unit hyperbola and the special unitary group SU(1,1).
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The word is derived from Latin *versari* = "to turn" with the suffix *-or* forming a noun from the verb (i.e.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] It was introduced by William Rowan Hamilton in the 1840s in the context of his quaternion theory.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] The term "versor" is generalised in geometric algebra to indicate a member R of the algebra that can be expressed as the product of invertible vectors, $R=v_{1}v_{2}\cdots v_{k}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Just as a quaternion versor u can be used to represent a rotation of a quaternion q with mapping $q\mapsto u^{-1}qu$ , so can a versor R in Geometric Algebra be used to represent the result of k reflections on a member A of the algebra with mapping $A\mapsto (-1)^{k}RAR^{-1}$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] A rotation can be considered the result of two reflections, so it turns out a quaternion versor u can be identified as a 2-versor $R=v_{1}v_{2}$ in the geometric algebra of three real dimensions ${\mathcal {G}}(3,0)$ .
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] In a departure from Hamilton's definition, multivector versors are not required to have unit norm, just to be invertible.
[src:quaternions-octonions/versor] Normalisation can still be useful however, so it is convenient to designate versors as *unit versors* in a geometric algebra if $R{\tilde {R}}=\pm 1$ , where the tilde denotes reversion of the versor.
